04446nam a22005535i 9780773599673DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2016436385  a97807735996737 a10.1515/97807735996732doi  a(DE-B1597)654512  a(OCoLC)948827336  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aE99.A13bB247 2016 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a971.4004/97342231 aBarman, Jean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAbenaki Daring :bThe Life and Writings of Noel Annance, 1792-1869 /cJean Barman. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource :b14 illustrations, 2 maps, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Indigenous and Northern Studies ;v8800tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAnnance’s Writings Reproduced in the Text -- tIllustrations, Maps, and Table -- tPreface -- tChronology -- tIntroduction -- tAn Inheritance of Wary Engagement -- tOf Abenaki Daring and Captivity Narratives -- tTaking a Chance on Literacy’s Promise -- tPursuing Indigenous Inclusion -- tIn Search of Belonging -- tHopes for the Fur Trade -- tLetting Go -- tContesting Indigenous Exclusion -- tReturning Home to Captivity Narratives’ Legacies -- tLand No More -- tTo Belong or Not to Belong -- tPostscript -- tNoel Annance's Journal of the Voyage from Fort George to the Fraser River, 18 November to 31 December 1824 -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn Abenaki born in St Francis, Quebec, Noel Annance (1792–1869), by virtue of two of his great-grandparents having been early white captives, attended Dartmouth College in New Hampshire. Determined to apply his privileged education, he was caught between two ways of being, neither of which accepted him among their numbers. Despite outstanding service as an officer in the War of 1812, Annance was too Indigenous to be allowed to succeed in the far west fur trade, and too schooled in outsiders’ ways to be accepted by those in charge on returning home. Annance did not crumple, but all his life dared the promise of literacy on his own behalf and on that of Indigenous peoples more generally. His doing so is tracked through his writings to government officials and others, some of which are reproduced in this volume. Annance’s life makes visible how the exclusionary policies towards Indigenous peoples, generally considered to have originated with the Indian Act of 1876, were being put in place upwards to half a century earlier. On account of his literacy, Annance’s story can be told. Recounting a life marked equally by success and failure, and by perseverance, Abenaki Daring speaks to similar barriers that to this day impede many educated Indigenous persons from realizing their life goals. To dare is no less essential than it was for Noel Annance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAbenaki IndianszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aAbenaki IndianszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359967340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773599673423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773599673/original  a978-3-11-127380-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-127630-4  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles